05919nam a22011655i 9781400832545DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212003nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97814008325457 a10.1515/97814008325452doi  a(DE-B1597)588922  a(OCoLC)1269268278  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aHIS0360002bisacsh1 aWeeks, Jim, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGettysburg :bMemory, Market, and an American Shrine /cJim Weeks. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2021] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b25 halftones.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPHASE ONE 1863-1884 A Genteel Summer Resort -- tChapter Two A Stream of Pilgrims -- tPHASE TWO 1884-1920 A Mecca for Patriots -- tChapter Three A Memorial of the Whole Struggle -- tChapter Four A Place for Tourists and the Oppressed -- tPHASE THREE 1920-1970 TV, Hot Bath, Cold War -- tChapter Five "These Are Touring Days": Mass Culture Transforms Gettysburg -- tChapter Six "Dad Got Us There in a Day": Automobiles and Family Touring -- tPHASE FOUR 1970-2000 Heritage Gettysburg -- tChapter Seven A Future in the Past -- tChapter Eight "It's 1863 All Over Again": Heritage Tourists -- tEPILOGUE: "The Most American Place in America" -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe site of North America's greatest battle is a national icon, a byword for the Civil War, and an American cliché. Described as "the most American place in America," Gettysburg is defended against commercial desecration like no other historic site. Yet even as schoolchildren learn to revere the place where Lincoln delivered his most famous speech, Gettysburg's image generates millions of dollars every year from touring, souvenirs, reenactments, films, games, collecting, and the Internet. Examining Gettysburg's place in American culture, this book finds that the selling of Gettysburg is older than the shrine itself.Gettysburg entered the market not with recent interest in the Civil War nor even with twentieth-century tourism but immediately after the battle. Founded by a modern industrial society with the capacity to deliver uniform images to millions, Gettysburg, from the very beginning, reflected the nation's marketing trends as much as its patriotism. Gettysburg's pilgrims--be they veterans, families on vacation, or Civil War reenactors--have always been modern consumers escaping from the world of work and responsibility even as they commemorate. And it is precisely this commodification of sacred ground, this tension between commerce and commemoration, that animates Gettysburg's popularity.Gettysburg continues to be a current rather than a past event, a site that reveals more about ourselves as Americans than the battle it remembers. Gettysburg is, as it has been since its famous battle, both a cash cow and a revered symbol of our most deeply held values.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans.  aChristmas.  aCold War.  aDouglass, Frederick.  aGettysburg Springs Hotel.  aGreenfield Village.  aHistoric Pathway.  aJack Paar Show.  aJacobs, Michael.  aLibby Prison.  aLincoln Highway.  aMeade, Margaretta.  aNew Age religion.  aPennsylvania College.  aPublic Works Administration.  aSabbatarianism.  aSoldiers' National Cemetery.  aU.S. War Department.  aVietnam.  aWilliamsburg, Virginia.  aanniversaries and celebrations.  aauthenticity.  ababy boomers.  abed and breakfasts.  acamping.  acomputers.  aconsumption.  adepartment stores.  aemancipation cel